    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Tuesday</p>
      <p>My Dearest Mate</p>
      <p>I quite agree in the wisdom of your remarks; but I think that I have perhaps led you slightly into an error as to the nature &amp; intensity of my dramatic wishes &amp; plans.</p>
      <p>I consider the dramatic representation as only one</p>
      <p>ingredient (tho' an important &amp; to me essential one), of far more enlarged views; &amp; I would on no account make it my main-stay.</p>
      <p>My genius in that line seems not unlikely to be so very prominent, that with very moderate cultivation I must even excel; but I never could look to excellence of mere representation being</p>
      <p>satisfactory to me as an ultimate goal, or exclusive object. I have however a curious instinct that until I have obtained these expressive powers to the utmost extent, that which will be really permanent in me cannot be fully developped; &amp; that as an instrument for working out of my own mind &amp; soul the great resources which I believe</p>
      <p>be deep hid beneath the surface, I must develop &amp; cultivate these more superficial &amp; transient arts &amp; means of expression. I consider that all my vocal &amp; dramatic studies will be merely an education &amp; preparation for that which is ultimately to be.--</p>
      <p>Now do you begin to comprehend my views?--</p>
      <p>Meanwhile I cannot describe to you my</p>
      <p>increasing tranquillity &amp; peace of mind, as well as daily improving health.</p>
      <p>Everyone is struck with the wonderful youth of my appearance, &amp; with a something free &amp; joyous in manner &amp; mien, very different from anything I have ever been.--</p>
      <p>There is much that is to me delightful in my present state altogether, or rather in the anticipation</p>
      <p>of the state to which I seem to be daily fast approaching. Hester says that it is evident I no longer seek excitements as excitements; &amp; that the Theatres are to me not places to which (as formerly) I must fly in order not to sit at home; but objects of lively interest for study; &amp; rather sought by me sometimes as a duty, for that purpose, when</p>
      <p>I should prefer sitting at home pursuing my avocations.</p>
      <p>She says that with infinitely more of daring, courage, &amp; independence, than she could have ever imagined, there is an increasing gentleness &amp; stability of mind which she never saw before in me.</p>
      <p>What will be my ultimate line, time only can show. I have my own impression about it; but until much has</p>
      <p>been worked out of me in various ways, I do not think any one can foresee.</p>
      <p>Besides, extraneous circumstances must of course much influence.--</p>
      <p>I will not however hesitate to tell you my impression. I think that to which all is tending is the development of a very high order of poetical genius; &amp; that poetry, in conjunction with musical composition, must be my</p>
      <p>destiny. And if so, it will be poetry of an unique kind;-- far more philosophical, &amp; higher in its nature than aught the world has perhaps yet seen.</p>
      <p>The impulse this way seems to me irresistible; but I have genius enough to perceive that a great poet, (this is what I call a great Poet), must</p>
      <p>go thro' a vast and arduous training; &amp; that to allow it to develop early or too soon would be ruinous in all respects. That I can write, I know; because I have written. And I write too with great facility. But I well know all I have before me; &amp; that before I give entire way to this powerful prompting of</p>
      <p>nature, I must see much, think much, study much, understand life in every phase, &amp; cultivate all the arts of expression practically &amp; for long &amp; long &amp; long.</p>
      <p>Just to show you that I can write, I send you a little thing which I did the other day. It was suggested to me by a German ballad of Schiller's; but I cannot call it either</p>
      <p>a translation, for (except the first stanza, which is rather close), it is entirely different from the original. Now, dear William, I had not intended to impart to you at present these recent occurances; but I feel from your late letters, that no one is so worthy of it. I had feared your disapproval, &amp; indeed that you would be pained &amp; disappointed;</p>
      <p>from a mis-comprehension of the nature of the case. It is doubtless all this wonderful &amp; curious change &amp; development in me, which has caused my illness; there has been an utter bouleversement in my mind &amp; body, &amp; now all the real &amp; natural genius is coming out;-- hitherto pent-up, unknown, unsuspected, even repressed.</p>
      <p>I cannot lament over the lateness of the</p>
      <p>development. Tho' I quite feel that there has been a frightful crisis in my existence during the past year; &amp; Heaven only knows what intense suffering &amp; agony I have gone thro'; &amp; how mad &amp; how reckless &amp; how desperate I have at times felt. Now all these dreadful things are passing away, &amp; my great powers seem to be</p>
      <p>finding their legitimate vents; my health to be more promising than perhaps ever in my life; &amp; my mind in all respects settling. But, Good God! None can ever know what formidable suffering has been my lot. Having stood it however, &amp; come out of it apparently unimpaired (tho' with deep &amp; ever-enduring traces of the fire), all will now do well. And I feel</p>
      <p>that every gentler &amp; social feeling is developping more &amp; more, as my imagination comes to feel surer prospects of employment &amp; vent.--</p>
      <p>But, Oh Heaven! may you, dear William, understand it all in its true light! For I tremble, lest I might receive any check from you! It might utterly blast me, slow tho' sure in its effects.--</p>
